61	class ExpectColumnStdevToBeBetween(ColumnAggregateExpectation):
62	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    Uses sample standard deviation (normalized by N-1).
65	
66	    ExpectColumnStdevToBeBetween is a \
67	    Column Aggregate Expectation.
68	
69	    Column Aggregate Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
70	    They are evaluated for a single column, and produce an aggregate Metric, such as a mean, standard deviation, number of unique values, column type, etc.
71	    If that Metric meets the conditions you set, the Expectation considers that data valid.
72	
73	    Args:
74	        column (str): \
75	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
76	        min_value (float or None): \
77	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
78	        max_value (float or None): \
79	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
80	        strict_min (boolean): \
81	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION} default=False.
82	        strict_max (boolean): \
83	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION} default=False.
84	
85	    Other Parameters:
86	        result_format (str or None): \
87	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
88	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
89	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
90	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
91	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
92	        meta (dict or None): \
93	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
94	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
95	
96	    Returns:
97	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
98	
99	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
100	
101	    Notes:
102	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive unless strict_min or strict_max are set to True.
103	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
104	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound
105	        * observed_value field in the result object is customized for this expectation to be a float \
106	          representing the true standard deviation for the column
107	
108	    See Also:
109	        [ExpectColumnMeanToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_mean_to_be_between)

74	        column (str): \
75	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
76	        min_value (float or None): \
77	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
78	        max_value (float or None): \
79	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
80	        strict_min (boolean): \
81	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION} default=False.
82	        strict_max (boolean): \
83	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION} default=False.
84	
85	    Other Parameters:
86	        result_format (str or None): \
87	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
88	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
89	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
90	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
91	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
92	        meta (dict or None): \
93	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
94	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
95	
96	    Returns:
97	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
98	
99	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
100	
101	    Notes:
102	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive unless strict_min or strict_max are set to True.
103	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
104	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound
105	        * observed_value field in the result object is customized for this expectation to be a float \
106	          representing the true standard deviation for the column
107	
108	    See Also:
109	        [ExpectColumnMeanToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_mean_to_be_between)
110	        [ExpectColumnMedianToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_median_to_be_between)

65	    If that Metric meets the conditions you set, the Expectation considers that data valid.
66	
67	    Args:
68	        column (str): \
69	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
70	        min_value (comparable type or None): \
71	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
72	        max_value (comparable type or None): \
73	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
74	        strict_min (boolean): \
75	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION} default=False.
76	        strict_max (boolean): \
77	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION} default=False.
78	
79	    Other Parameters:
80	        result_format (str or None): \
81	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
82	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
83	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
84	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
85	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
86	        meta (dict or None): \
87	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
88	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
89	
90	    Returns:
91	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
92	
93	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
94	
95	    Notes:
96	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive unless strict_min or strict_max are set to True.
97	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
98	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound
99	        * observed_value field in the result object is customized for this expectation to be a list \
100	          representing the actual column sum
101	
102	    Supported Data Sources:
103	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
105	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

107	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

92	
93	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
94	
95	    Notes:
96	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive unless strict_min or strict_max are set to True.
97	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
98	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound
99	        * observed_value field in the result object is customized for this expectation to be a list \
100	          representing the actual column sum
101	
102	    Supported Data Sources:
103	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

57	class ExpectColumnSumToBeBetween(ColumnAggregateExpectation):
58	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
59	
60	    ExpectColumnSumToBeBetween is a \
61	    Column Aggregate Expectation.
62	
63	    Column Aggregate Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
64	    They are evaluated for a single column, and produce an aggregate Metric, such as a mean, standard deviation, number of unique values, column type, etc.
65	    If that Metric meets the conditions you set, the Expectation considers that data valid.
66	
67	    Args:
68	        column (str): \
69	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
70	        min_value (comparable type or None): \
71	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
72	        max_value (comparable type or None): \
73	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
74	        strict_min (boolean): \
75	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION} default=False.
76	        strict_max (boolean): \
77	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION} default=False.
78	
79	    Other Parameters:
80	        result_format (str or None): \
81	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
82	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
83	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
84	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
85	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
86	        meta (dict or None): \
87	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
88	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
89	
90	    Returns:
91	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
92	
93	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
94	
95	    Notes:
96	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive unless strict_min or strict_max are set to True.
97	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
98	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound
99	        * observed_value field in the result object is customized for this expectation to be a list \
100	          representing the actual column sum
101	
102	    Supported Data Sources:
103	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

58

60	
61	    Args:
62	        column (str): {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    Other Parameters:
65	        column_index (int or None, optional): {COLUMN_INDEX_DESCRIPTION}
66	        result_format (str or None, optional): \
67	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
68	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
69	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None, optional): \
70	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
71	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
72	        meta (dict or None, optional): \
73	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
74	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
75	
76	    Returns:
77	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
78	
79	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
80	
81	    Supported Data Sources:
82	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_unique_value_count_to_be_between.py:65
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
64	class ExpectColumnUniqueValueCountToBeBetween(ColumnAggregateExpectation):
65	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
66	
67	    ExpectColumnUniqueValueCountToBeBetween is a \
68	    Column Aggregate Expectation.
69	
70	    Column Aggregate Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
71	    They are evaluated for a single column, and produce an aggregate Metric, such as a mean, standard deviation, number of unique values, column type, etc.
72	    If that Metric meets the conditions you set, the Expectation considers that data valid.
73	
74	    Args:
75	        column (str): \
76	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
77	        min_value (int or None): \
78	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
79	        max_value (int or None): \
80	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
81	        strict_min (bool): \
82	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION}
83	        strict_max (bool): \
84	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION}
85	
86	    Other Parameters:
87	        result_format (str or None): \
88	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
89	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
90	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
91	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
92	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
93	        meta (dict or None): \
94	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
95	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
96	
97	    Returns:
98	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
99	
100	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
101	
102	    Notes:
103	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive.
104	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
105	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound
106	        * observed_value field in the result object is customized for this expectation to be an int \
107	          representing the number of unique values the column
108	
109	    See Also:
110	        [ExpectColumnProportionOfUniqueValuesToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_proportion_of_unique_values_to_be_between)
111	
112	    Supported Data Sources:
113	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
114	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
115	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
116	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
117	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
118	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
119	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
120	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
121	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[8]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
122	
123	    Data Quality Issues:
124	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}
125

89	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
90	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
91	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
92	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
93	        meta (dict or None): \
94	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
95	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
96	
97	    Returns:
98	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
99	
100	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
101	
102	    Notes:
103	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive.
104	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
105	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound
106	        * observed_value field in the result object is customized for this expectation to be an int \
107	          representing the number of unique values the column
108	
109	    See Also:
110	        [ExpectColumnProportionOfUniqueValuesToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_proportion_of_unique_values_to_be_between)
111	
112	    Supported Data Sources:
113	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
114	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

69	
70	    Column Aggregate Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
71	    They are evaluated for a single column, and produce an aggregate Metric, such as a mean, standard deviation, number of unique values, column type, etc.

98	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
99	
100	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
101	
102	    Notes:
103	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive.
104	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
105	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound
106	        * observed_value field in the result object is customized for this expectation to be an int \
107	          representing the number of unique values the column
108	
109	    See Also:
110	        [ExpectColumnProportionOfUniqueValuesToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_proportion_of_unique_values_to_be_between)
111	
112	    Supported Data Sources:
113	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

64	class ExpectColumnUniqueValueCountToBeBetween(ColumnAggregateExpectation):
65	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
66	
67	    ExpectColumnUniqueValueCountToBeBetween is a \
68	    Column Aggregate Expectation.
69	
70	    Column Aggregate Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
71	    They are evaluated for a single column, and produce an aggregate Metric, such as a mean, standard deviation, number of unique values, column type, etc.
72	    If that Metric meets the conditions you set, the Expectation considers that data valid.
73	
74	    Args:
75	        column (str): \
76	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
77	        min_value (int or None): \
78	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
79	        max_value (int or None): \
80	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
81	        strict_min (bool): \
82	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION}
83	        strict_max (bool): \
84	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION}
85	
86	    Other Parameters:
87	        result_format (str or None): \
88	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
89	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
90	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
91	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
92	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
93	        meta (dict or None): \
94	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
95	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
96	
97	    Returns:
98	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
99	
100	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
101	
102	    Notes:

104	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound
105	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound

107	          representing the number of unique values the column

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_value_lengths_to_be_between.py:79
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
78	class ExpectColumnValueLengthsToBeBetween(ColumnMapExpectation):
79	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
80	
81	    This expectation only works for string-type values. Invoking it on ints or floats will raise a TypeError.
82	
83	    ExpectColumnValueLengthsToBeBetween is a \
84	    Column Map Expectation.
85	
86	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
87	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
88	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
89	
90	    Args:
91	        column (str): \
92	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
93	        min_value (int or None): \
94	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
95	        max_value (int or None): \
96	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
97	        strict_min (boolean): \
98	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION} Default=False
99	        strict_max (boolean): \
100	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION} Default=False
101	
102	    Other Parameters:
103	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
104	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
105	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
106	        result_format (str or None): \
107	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
108	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
109	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
110	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
111	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
112	        meta (dict or None): \
113	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
114	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
115	
116	    Returns:
117	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
118	
119	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
120	
121	    Notes:
122	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive.
123	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
124	          no minimum.
125	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
126	          no maximum.
127	
128	    See Also:
129	        [ExpectColumnValueLengthsToEqual](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_value_lengths_to_equal)
130	
131	    Supported Data Sources:
132	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
133	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
134	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
135	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
136	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
137	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
138	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

106	        result_format (str or None): \
107	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
108	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
109	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
110	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
111	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
112	        meta (dict or None): \
113	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
114	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
115	
116	    Returns:
117	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
118	
119	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
120	
121	    Notes:
122	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive.
123	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
124	          no minimum.
125	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
126	          no maximum.
127	
128	    See Also:
129	        [ExpectColumnValueLengthsToEqual](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_value_lengths_to_equal)
130	
131	    Supported Data Sources:
132	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
133	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
78	class ExpectColumnValueLengthsToBeBetween(ColumnMapExpectation):
79	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
80	
81	    This expectation only works for string-type values. Invoking it on ints or floats will raise a TypeError.
82	
83	    ExpectColumnValueLengthsToBeBetween is a \
84	    Column Map Expectation.
85	
86	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
87	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
88	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
89	
90	    Args:
91	        column (str): \
92	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
93	        min_value (int or None): \
94	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
95	        max_value (int or None): \
96	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
97	        strict_min (boolean): \
98	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION} Default=False
99	        strict_max (boolean): \
100	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION} Default=False
101	
102	    Other Parameters:
103	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
104	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
105	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
106	        result_format (str or None): \
107	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
108	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
109	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
110	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
111	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
112	        meta (dict or None): \
113	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
114	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
115	
116	    Returns:
117	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
118	
119	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
120	
121	    Notes:
122	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive.
123	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
124	          no minimum.
125	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
126	          no maximum.
127	
128	    See Also:
129	        [ExpectColumnValueLengthsToEqual](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_value_lengths_to_equal)

60	    This expectation only works for string-type values. Invoking it on ints or floats will raise a TypeError.
61	
62	    ExpectColumnValueLengthsToEqual is a \
63	    Column Map Expectation.
64	
65	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
66	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
67	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
68	
69	    Args:
70	        column (str): \
71	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
72	        value (int): \
73	            {VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
74	
75	    Other Parameters:
76	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
77	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
78	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
79	        result_format (str or None): \
80	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
81	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
82	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
83	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
84	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
85	        meta (dict or None): \
86	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
87	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
88	
89	    Returns:
90	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
91	
92	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
93	
94	    See Also:
95	        [ExpectColumnValueLengthsToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_value_lengths_to_be_between)

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
57	class ExpectColumnValueLengthsToEqual(ColumnMapExpectation):
58	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
59	
60	    This expectation only works for string-type values. Invoking it on ints or floats will raise a TypeError.
61	
62	    ExpectColumnValueLengthsToEqual is a \
63	    Column Map Expectation.
64	
65	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
66	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
67	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
68	
69	    Args:
70	        column (str): \
71	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
72	        value (int): \
73	            {VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
74	
75	    Other Parameters:
76	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
77	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
78	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
79	        result_format (str or None): \
80	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
81	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
82	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
83	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
84	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
85	        meta (dict or None): \
86	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
87	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
88	
89	    Returns:
90	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
91	
92	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
93	
94	    See Also:
95	        [ExpectColumnValueLengthsToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_value_lengths_to_be_between)
96	
97	    Supported Data Sources:
98	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
99	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

78	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
79	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
80	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
81	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
82	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
83	        meta (dict or None): \
84	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
85	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
86	
87	    Returns:
88	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
89	
90	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.

   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_value_z_scores_to_be_less_than.py:53
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
52	class ExpectColumnValueZScoresToBeLessThan(ColumnMapExpectation):
53	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
54	
55	    ExpectColumnValueZScoresToBeLessThan is a \
56	    Column Map Expectation \
57	    for typed-column backends, and also for PandasExecutionEngine where the column \
58	    dtype and provided type_ are unambiguous constraints \
59	    (any dtype except 'object' or dtype of 'object' with type_ specified as 'object').
60	
61	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
62	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
63	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
64	
65	    Args:
66	        column (str): \
67	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
68	        threshold (number): \
69	            {THRESHOLD_DESCRIPTION}
70	        double_sided (boolean): \
71	            {DOUBLE_SIDED_DESCRIPTION}
72	
73	    Other Parameters:
74	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
75	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
76	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
77	        result_format (str or None): \
78	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
79	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
80	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
81	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
82	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
83	        meta (dict or None): \
84	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
85	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
86	
87	    Returns:
88	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
89	
90	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
91	
92	    Supported Data Sources:
93	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
94	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
95	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_be_between.py:63
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
62	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeBetween(ColumnMapExpectation):
63	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
64	
65	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeBetween is a \
66	    Column Map Expectation
67	
68	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
69	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
70	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
71	
72	    Args:
73	        column (str): \
74	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
75	        min_value (comparable type or None): \
76	        {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
77	        max_value (comparable type or None): \
78	        {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
79	        strict_min (boolean): \
80	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION} Default=False.
81	        strict_max (boolean): \
82	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION} Default=False.
83	
84	    Other Parameters:
85	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
86	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
87	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly).
88	        result_format (str or None): \
89	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
90	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
91	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
92	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
93	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
94	        meta (dict or None): \
95	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
96	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
97	
98	    Returns:
99	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
100	
101	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
102	
103	    Notes:
104	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive unless strict_min or strict_max are set to True.
105	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and there is no minimum value checked.
106	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and there is no maximum value checked.
107	
108	    See Also:
109	        [ExpectColumnValueLengthsToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_value_lengths_to_be_between)
110	
111	    Supported Data Sources:
112	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
113	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
114	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
115	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
116	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
117	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
118	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
119	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
120	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[8]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
121	
122	    Data Quality Issues:
123	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}
124

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
62	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeBetween(ColumnMapExpectation):
63	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
64	
65	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeBetween is a \
66	    Column Map Expectation
67	
68	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
69	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
70	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
71	
72	    Args:
73	        column (str): \
74	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
75	        min_value (comparable type or None): \
76	        {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
77	        max_value (comparable type or None): \
78	        {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
79	        strict_min (boolean): \
80	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION} Default=False.
81	        strict_max (boolean): \
82	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION} Default=False.
83	
84	    Other Parameters:
85	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
86	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
87	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly).
88	        result_format (str or None): \
89	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
90	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
91	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
92	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
93	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
94	        meta (dict or None): \
95	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
96	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
97	
98	    Returns:
99	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
100	
101	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
102	
103	    Notes:
104	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive unless strict_min or strict_max are set to True.
105	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and there is no minimum value checked.
106	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and there is no maximum value checked.
107	
108	    See Also:
109	        [ExpectColumnValueLengthsToBeBetween](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_value_lengths_to_be_between)
110	
111	    Supported Data Sources:

   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_be_in_set.py:66
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
65	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeInSet(ColumnMapExpectation):
66	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
67	
68	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeInSet is a \
69	    Column Map Expectation.
70	
71	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
72	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
73	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
74	
75	    Args:
76	        column (str): \
77	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
78	        value_set (set-like): \
79	            {VALUE_SET_DESCRIPTION}
80	
81	    Other Parameters:
82	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
83	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
84	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
85	        result_format (str or None): \
86	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
87	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
88	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
89	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
90	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
91	        meta (dict or None): \
92	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
93	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
94	
95	    Returns:
96	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
97	
98	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
99	
100	    See Also:
101	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeInSet](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_be_in_set)
102	
103	    Supported Data Sources:
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
105	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
106	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
107	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
108	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
109	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
110	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
111	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
112	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[8]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
113	
114	    Data Quality Issues:
115	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}

   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_be_in_set.py:66
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
65	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeInSet(ColumnMapExpectation):
66	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
67	
68	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeInSet is a \
69	    Column Map Expectation.
70	
71	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
72	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
73	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
74	
75	    Args:
76	        column (str): \
77	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
78	        value_set (set-like): \
79	            {VALUE_SET_DESCRIPTION}
80	
81	    Other Parameters:
82	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
83	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
84	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
85	        result_format (str or None): \
86	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
87	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
88	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
89	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
90	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
91	        meta (dict or None): \
92	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
93	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
94	
95	    Returns:
96	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
97	
98	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
99	
100	    See Also:
101	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeInSet](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_be_in_set)
102	
103	    Supported Data Sources:
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
105	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
106	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
107	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
108	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
109	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

111	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_be_in_type_list.py:67
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
66	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeInTypeList(ColumnMapExpectation):
67	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
68	
69	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeInTypeList is a \
70	    Column Map Expectation \
71	    for typed-column backends, and also for Pandas Datasources where the column dtype provides an \
72	    unambiguous constraints (any dtype except 'object').
73	
74	    For Pandas columns with dtype of 'object' ExpectColumnValuesToBeInTypeList will \
75	    independently check each row's type.
76	
77	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
78	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
79	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
80	
81	    Args:
82	        column (str): \
83	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
84	        type_list (list[str] or None): \
85	            {TYPE_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
86	            For example, valid types for Pandas Datasources include any numpy dtype values \
87	            (such as 'int64') or native python types (such as 'int'), whereas valid types for a \
88	            SqlAlchemy Datasource include types named by the current driver such as 'INTEGER' \
89	            in most SQL dialects and 'TEXT' in dialects such as postgresql. Valid types for \
90	            Spark Datasources include 'StringType', 'BooleanType' and other pyspark-defined type names.
91	
92	    Other Parameters:
93	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
94	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
95	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
96	        result_format (str or None): \
97	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
98	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
99	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
100	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
101	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
102	        meta (dict or None): \
103	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
104	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
105	
106	    Returns:
107	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
108	
109	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
110	
111	    See also:
112	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_of_type)
113	
114	    Supported Data Sources:
115	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
116	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
117	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
118	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
119	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
120	
121	    Data Quality Issues:
122	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}
123

78	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
79	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
80	
81	    Args:
82	        column (str): \
83	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
84	        type_list (list[str] or None): \
85	            {TYPE_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
86	            For example, valid types for Pandas Datasources include any numpy dtype values \
87	            (such as 'int64') or native python types (such as 'int'), whereas valid types for a \
88	            SqlAlchemy Datasource include types named by the current driver such as 'INTEGER' \
89	            in most SQL dialects and 'TEXT' in dialects such as postgresql. Valid types for \
90	            Spark Datasources include 'StringType', 'BooleanType' and other pyspark-defined type names.
91	
92	    Other Parameters:
93	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
94	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
95	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
96	        result_format (str or None): \
97	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
98	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
99	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
100	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
101	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
102	        meta (dict or None): \
103	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
104	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
105	
106	    Returns:
107	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
108	
109	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
110	
111	    See also:
112	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_of_type)
113	
114	    Supported Data Sources:
115	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
116	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
117	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
118	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
119	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
120	
121	    Data Quality Issues:
122	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}

87	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
88	        meta (dict or None): \
89	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
90	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
91	
92	    Returns:
93	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
94	
95	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
96	
97	    See Also:
98	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeNull](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_be_null)
99	
100	    Supported Data Sources:
101	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
102	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

65	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeNull(ColumnMapExpectation):
66	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
67	
68	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeNull is a \
69	    Column Map Expectation.
70	
71	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
72	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
73	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
74	
75	    Args:
76	        column (str): \
77	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
78	
79	    Other Parameters:
80	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
81	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
82	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
83	        result_format (str or None): \
84	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
85	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
86	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
87	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
88	        meta (dict or None): \
89	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
90	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
91	
92	    Returns:
93	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
94	
95	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
96	
97	    See Also:
98	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeNull](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_be_null)
99	
100	    Supported Data Sources:
101	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
102	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_be_of_type.py:92
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
91	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType(ColumnMapExpectation):
92	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
93	
94	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType is a \
95	    Column Map Expectation \
96	    for typed-column backends, and also for Pandas Datasources where the column dtype and provided \
97	    type_ are unambiguous constraints (any dtype except 'object' or dtype of 'object' with \
98	    type_ specified as 'object').
99	
100	    For Pandas columns with dtype of 'object' ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType will
101	    independently check each row's type.
102	
103	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
104	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
105	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
106	
107	    Args:
108	        column (str): \
109	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
110	        type\\_ (str): \
111	            {TYPE__DESCRIPTION}
112	            For example, valid types for Pandas Datasources include any numpy dtype values \
113	            (such as 'int64') or native python types (such as 'int'), whereas valid types \
114	            for a SqlAlchemy Datasource include types named by the current driver such as 'INTEGER' \
115	            in most SQL dialects and 'TEXT' in dialects such as postgresql. \
116	            Valid types for Spark Datasources include 'StringType', 'BooleanType' and other \
117	            pyspark-defined type names. Note that the strings representing these \
118	            types are sometimes case-sensitive. For instance, with a Pandas backend `timestamp` \
119	            will be unrecognized and fail the expectation, while `Timestamp` would pass with valid data.
120	
121	    Other Parameters:
122	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
123	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
124	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
125	        result_format (str or None): \
126	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
127	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
128	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
129	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
130	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
131	        meta (dict or None): \
132	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
133	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
134	
135	    Returns:
136	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
137	
138	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
139	
140	    See also:
141	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeInTypeList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_in_type_list)
142	
143	    Supported Data Sources:
144	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
145	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
146	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
147	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
148	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
149	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
150	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
151	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
152	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[8]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
153	
154	    Data Quality Issues:
155	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_be_of_type.py:92
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
91	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType(ColumnMapExpectation):
92	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
93	
94	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType is a \
95	    Column Map Expectation \
96	    for typed-column backends, and also for Pandas Datasources where the column dtype and provided \
97	    type_ are unambiguous constraints (any dtype except 'object' or dtype of 'object' with \
98	    type_ specified as 'object').
99	
100	    For Pandas columns with dtype of 'object' ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType will
101	    independently check each row's type.
102	
103	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
104	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
105	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
106	
107	    Args:
108	        column (str): \
109	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
110	        type\\_ (str): \
111	            {TYPE__DESCRIPTION}
112	            For example, valid types for Pandas Datasources include any numpy dtype values \
113	            (such as 'int64') or native python types (such as 'int'), whereas valid types \
114	            for a SqlAlchemy Datasource include types named by the current driver such as 'INTEGER' \
115	            in most SQL dialects and 'TEXT' in dialects such as postgresql. \
116	            Valid types for Spark Datasources include 'StringType', 'BooleanType' and other \
117	            pyspark-defined type names. Note that the strings representing these \
118	            types are sometimes case-sensitive. For instance, with a Pandas backend `timestamp` \
119	            will be unrecognized and fail the expectation, while `Timestamp` would pass with valid data.
120	
121	    Other Parameters:
122	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
123	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
124	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
125	        result_format (str or None): \
126	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
127	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
128	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
129	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
130	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
131	        meta (dict or None): \
132	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
133	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
134	
135	    Returns:
136	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
137	
138	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
139	
140	    See also:
141	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeInTypeList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_in_type_list)
142	
143	    Supported Data Sources:
144	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
145	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
146	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
147	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
148	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
149	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
150	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
151	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
152	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[8]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

155	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}

93	
94	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType is a \
95	    Column Map Expectation \
96	    for typed-column backends, and also for Pandas Datasources where the column dtype and provided \

113	            (such as 'int64') or native python types (such as 'int'), whereas valid types \

116	            Valid types for Spark Datasources include 'StringType', 'BooleanType' and other \

125	        result_format (str or None): \

127	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
128	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
129	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
130	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
131	        meta (dict or None): \
132	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
133	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
134	
135	    Returns:
136	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
137	
138	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
