105	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
106	
107	    Args:
108	        column (str): \
109	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
110	        type\\_ (str): \
111	            {TYPE__DESCRIPTION}
112	            For example, valid types for Pandas Datasources include any numpy dtype values \
113	            (such as 'int64') or native python types (such as 'int'), whereas valid types \
114	            for a SqlAlchemy Datasource include types named by the current driver such as 'INTEGER' \
115	            in most SQL dialects and 'TEXT' in dialects such as postgresql. \
116	            Valid types for Spark Datasources include 'StringType', 'BooleanType' and other \
117	            pyspark-defined type names. Note that the strings representing these \
118	            types are sometimes case-sensitive. For instance, with a Pandas backend `timestamp` \
119	            will be unrecognized and fail the expectation, while `Timestamp` would pass with valid data.
120	
121	    Other Parameters:
122	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
123	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
124	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
125	        result_format (str or None): \
126	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
127	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
128	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
129	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
130	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
131	        meta (dict or None): \
132	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
133	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
134	
135	    Returns:
136	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
137	
138	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
139	
140	    See also:
141	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeInTypeList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_in_type_list)
142	
143	    Supported Data Sources:
144	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
145	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
146	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
147	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
148	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
149	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
150	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
151	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
152	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[8]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
91	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType(ColumnMapExpectation):
92	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
93	
94	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType is a \
95	    Column Map Expectation \
96	    for typed-column backends, and also for Pandas Datasources where the column dtype and provided \
97	    type_ are unambiguous constraints (any dtype except 'object' or dtype of 'object' with \
98	    type_ specified as 'object').
99	
100	    For Pandas columns with dtype of 'object' ExpectColumnValuesToBeOfType will
101	    independently check each row's type.
102	
103	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
104	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
105	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
106	
107	    Args:
108	        column (str): \
109	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
110	        type\\_ (str): \
111	            {TYPE__DESCRIPTION}
112	            For example, valid types for Pandas Datasources include any numpy dtype values \
113	            (such as 'int64') or native python types (such as 'int'), whereas valid types \
114	            for a SqlAlchemy Datasource include types named by the current driver such as 'INTEGER' \
115	            in most SQL dialects and 'TEXT' in dialects such as postgresql. \
116	            Valid types for Spark Datasources include 'StringType', 'BooleanType' and other \
117	            pyspark-defined type names. Note that the strings representing these \
118	            types are sometimes case-sensitive. For instance, with a Pandas backend `timestamp` \
119	            will be unrecognized and fail the expectation, while `Timestamp` would pass with valid data.
120	
121	    Other Parameters:
122	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
123	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
124	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
125	        result_format (str or None): \
126	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
127	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
128	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
129	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
130	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
131	        meta (dict or None): \
132	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
133	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
134	
135	    Returns:
136	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
137	
138	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
139	
140	    See also:
141	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeInTypeList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_in_type_list)
142	
143	    Supported Data Sources:
144	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
145	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
146	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
147	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
148	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
149	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

53	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeUnique(ColumnMapExpectation):
54	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
55	
56	    This expectation detects duplicates. All duplicated values are counted as exceptions.
57	
58	    For example, [1, 2, 3, 3, 3] will return [3, 3, 3] in result.exceptions_list, with \
59	    unexpected_percent = 60.0.
60	
61	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeUnique is a \
62	    Column Map Expectation
63	
64	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
65	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
66	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
67	
68	    Args:
69	        column (str): \
70	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
71	
72	    Other Parameters:
73	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
74	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
75	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly).
76	        result_format (str or None): \
77	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
78	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
79	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
80	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
81	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
82	        meta (dict or None): \
83	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
84	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
85	
86	    Returns:
87	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
88	
89	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
90	
91	    Supported Data Sources:
92	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_be_unique.py:54
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
53	class ExpectColumnValuesToBeUnique(ColumnMapExpectation):
54	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
55	
56	    This expectation detects duplicates. All duplicated values are counted as exceptions.
57	
58	    For example, [1, 2, 3, 3, 3] will return [3, 3, 3] in result.exceptions_list, with \
59	    unexpected_percent = 60.0.
60	
61	    ExpectColumnValuesToBeUnique is a \
62	    Column Map Expectation
63	
64	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
65	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
66	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
67	
68	    Args:
69	        column (str): \
70	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
71	
72	    Other Parameters:
73	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
74	            Successful if at least mostly fraction of values match the expectation. \
75	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly).
76	        result_format (str or None): \
77	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
78	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
79	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
80	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
81	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
82	        meta (dict or None): \
83	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
84	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
85	
86	    Returns:
87	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
88	
89	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
90	
91	    Supported Data Sources:
92	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
93	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
94	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
95	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
96	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
97	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
98	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
99	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
100	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[8]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
101	
102	    Data Quality Issues:
103	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}

75	        result_format (str or None): \
76	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
77	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
78	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
79	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
80	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
81	        meta (dict or None): \
82	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
83	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
84	
85	    Returns:
86	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)

55	class ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePattern(ColumnMapExpectation):
56	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
57	
58	    ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePattern is a \
59	    Column Map Expectation.
60	
61	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
62	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
63	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
64	
65	    Args:
66	        column (str): \
67	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
68	        like_pattern (str): \
69	            {LIKE_PATTERN_DESCRIPTION}

75	        result_format (str or None): \
76	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
77	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
78	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
79	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
80	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
81	        meta (dict or None): \
82	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
83	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).

82	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
83	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).

61	class ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePatternList(ColumnMapExpectation):
62	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePatternList is a \
65	    Column Map Expectation.
66	
67	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
68	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
69	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
70	
71	    Args:
72	        column (str): \
73	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
74	        like_pattern_list (List[str]): \
75	            {LIKE_PATTERN_DESCRIPTION}
76	        match_on (string): \
77	            {MATCH_ON_DESCRIPTION}
78	
79	    Other Parameters:
80	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
81	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
82	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
83	        result_format (str or None): \
84	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
85	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
86	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
87	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
88	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
89	        meta (dict or None): \
90	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
91	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
92	
93	    Returns:
94	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
61	class ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePatternList(ColumnMapExpectation):
62	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePatternList is a \
65	    Column Map Expectation.
66	
67	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
68	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
69	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
70	
71	    Args:
72	        column (str): \
73	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
74	        like_pattern_list (List[str]): \
75	            {LIKE_PATTERN_DESCRIPTION}
76	        match_on (string): \
77	            {MATCH_ON_DESCRIPTION}
78	
79	    Other Parameters:
80	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
81	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
82	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
83	        result_format (str or None): \
84	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
85	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
86	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
87	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
88	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
89	        meta (dict or None): \
90	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
91	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
92	
93	    Returns:
94	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
95	
96	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
97	
98	    See Also:
99	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegex](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_regex)
100	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegexList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_regex_list)
101	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegex](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_regex)
102	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegexList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_regex_list)
103	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePattern](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_like_pattern)
104	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchLikePattern](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_like_pattern)
105	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchLikePatternList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_like_pattern_list)
106	
107	    Supported Data Sources:
108	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
109	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
110	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
111	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
55	class ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegex(ColumnMapExpectation):
56	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
57	
58	    Valid matches can be found \
59	    anywhere in the string, for example "[at]+" will identify the following strings as expected: "cat", "hat", \
60	    "aa", "a", and "t", and the following strings as unexpected: "fish", "dog".
61	
62	    ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegex is a \
63	    Column Map Expectation.
64	
65	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
66	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
67	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
68	
69	    Args:
70	        column (str): \
71	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
72	        regex (str): \
73	            {REGEX_DESCRIPTION}
74	
75	    Other Parameters:
76	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
77	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
78	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
79	        result_format (str or None): \
80	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
81	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
82	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
83	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
84	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
85	        meta (dict or None): \
86	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
87	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
88	
89	    Returns:
90	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
91	
92	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
93	
94	    See Also:
95	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegexList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_regex_list)
96	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegex](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_regex)
97	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegexList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_regex_list)

   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_match_regex.py:56
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
55	class ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegex(ColumnMapExpectation):
56	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
57	
58	    Valid matches can be found \
59	    anywhere in the string, for example "[at]+" will identify the following strings as expected: "cat", "hat", \
60	    "aa", "a", and "t", and the following strings as unexpected: "fish", "dog".
61	
62	    ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegex is a \
63	    Column Map Expectation.
64	
65	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
66	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
67	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
68	
69	    Args:
70	        column (str): \
71	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
72	        regex (str): \
73	            {REGEX_DESCRIPTION}
74	
75	    Other Parameters:
76	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
77	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
78	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
79	        result_format (str or None): \
80	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
81	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
82	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
83	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
84	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
85	        meta (dict or None): \
86	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
87	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
88	
89	    Returns:
90	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
91	
92	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
93	
94	    See Also:
95	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegexList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_regex_list)
96	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegex](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_regex)
97	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegexList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_regex_list)
98	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePattern](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_like_pattern)
99	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchLikePatternList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_like_pattern_list)
100	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchLikePattern](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_like_pattern)
101	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchLikePatternList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_like_pattern_list)
102	
103	    Supported Data Sources:
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
105	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
106	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

88	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
89	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
90	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
91	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
92	        meta (dict or None): \
93	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
94	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
95	
96	    Returns:
97	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
98	
99	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
100

62	class ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegexList(ColumnMapExpectation):
63	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
64	
65	    Matches can be anywhere in the string.
66	
67	    ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegexList is a \
68	    Column Map Expectation.
69	
70	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
71	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
72	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
73	
74	    Args:
75	        column (str): \
76	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
77	        regex_list (list): \
78	            {REGEX_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
79	        match_on (string): \
80	            {MATCH_ON_DESCRIPTION}
81	
82	    Other Parameters:
83	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
84	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
85	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly).
86	        result_format (str or None): \
87	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
88	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
89	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
90	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
91	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
92	        meta (dict or None): \
93	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
94	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
95	
96	    Returns:
97	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
98	
99	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.

63	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
64	
65	    Matches can be anywhere in the string.
66	
67	    ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegexList is a \
68	    Column Map Expectation.
69	
70	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
71	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
72	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
73

88	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
89	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
90	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \

94	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).

58	class ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeInSet(ColumnMapExpectation):

60	
61	    ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeInSet is a \
62	    Column Map Expectation.
63	
64	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
65	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
66	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
67	
68	    Args:
69	        column (str): \
70	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
71	        value_set (set-like): \

80	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
81	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
82	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
83	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).

64	class ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeNull(ColumnMapExpectation):
65	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
66	
67	    To be counted as an exception, values must be explicitly null or missing, such as a NULL in PostgreSQL or an
68	    np.NaN in pandas. Empty strings don't count as null unless they have been coerced to a null type.
69	
70	    ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeNull is a \
71	    Column Map Expectation.
72	
73	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
74	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
75	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
76	
77	    Args:
78	        column (str): \
79	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
80	
81	    Other Parameters:
82	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
83	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
84	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
85	        result_format (str or None): \
86	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
87	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
88	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
89	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
90	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
91	        meta (dict or None): \
92	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
93	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).

95	    Returns:
96	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)

103	    Supported Data Sources:
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

86	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
87	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
88	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
89	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
90	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
91	        meta (dict or None): \
92	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
93	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
94	
95	    Returns:
96	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
97	
98	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
99	
100	    See Also:
101	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeNull](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_null)
102	
103	    Supported Data Sources:
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
105	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_not_be_null.py:65
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
64	class ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeNull(ColumnMapExpectation):
65	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
66	
67	    To be counted as an exception, values must be explicitly null or missing, such as a NULL in PostgreSQL or an
68	    np.NaN in pandas. Empty strings don't count as null unless they have been coerced to a null type.
69	
70	    ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeNull is a \
71	    Column Map Expectation.
72	
73	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
74	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
75	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
76	
77	    Args:
78	        column (str): \
79	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
80	
81	    Other Parameters:
82	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
83	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
84	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
85	        result_format (str or None): \
86	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
87	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
88	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
89	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
90	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
91	        meta (dict or None): \
92	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
93	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
94	
95	    Returns:
96	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
97	
98	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
99	
100	    See Also:
101	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeNull](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_null)
102	
103	    Supported Data Sources:
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
105	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
106	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
107	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
108	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

111	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations/expectations/core/expect_column_values_to_not_be_null.py:65
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
64	class ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeNull(ColumnMapExpectation):
65	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
66	
67	    To be counted as an exception, values must be explicitly null or missing, such as a NULL in PostgreSQL or an
68	    np.NaN in pandas. Empty strings don't count as null unless they have been coerced to a null type.
69	
70	    ExpectColumnValuesToNotBeNull is a \
71	    Column Map Expectation.
72	
73	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
74	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
75	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
76	
77	    Args:
78	        column (str): \
79	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
80	
81	    Other Parameters:
82	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
83	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
84	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
85	        result_format (str or None): \
86	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
87	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
88	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
89	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
90	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
91	        meta (dict or None): \
92	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
93	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
94	
95	    Returns:
96	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
97	
98	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
99	
100	    See Also:
101	        [ExpectColumnValuesToBeNull](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_be_null)
102	
103	    Supported Data Sources:
104	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
105	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
106	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
107	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
108	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[4]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
109	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[5]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
110	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[6]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
111	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[7]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
112	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[8]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
113	
114	    Data Quality Issues:
115	        {DATA_QUALITY_ISSUES[0]}
116

73	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
74	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
75	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
76	        meta (dict or None): \
77	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
78	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).

50	class ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchLikePattern(ColumnMapExpectation):
51	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
52	
53	    ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchLikePattern is a \
54	    Column Map Expectation.
55	
56	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
57	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
58	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
59	
60	    Args:
61	        column (str): \
62	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
63	        like_pattern (str): \
64	            {LIKE_PATTERN_DESCRIPTION}
65	
66	    Other Parameters:
67	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
68	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
69	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
70	        result_format (str or None): \
71	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
72	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
73	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
74	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
75	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
76	        meta (dict or None): \
77	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
78	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
79	
80	    Returns:
81	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
82	
83	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
84

77	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
78	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
79	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
80	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
81	        meta (dict or None): \
82	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
83	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
84	
85	    Returns:
86	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
87

55	class ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchLikePatternList(ColumnMapExpectation):
56	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
57	
58	    ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchLikePatternList is a \
59	    Column Map Expectation.
60	
61	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
62	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
63	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
64	
65	    Args:
66	        column (str): \
67	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
68	        like_pattern_list (List[str]): \
69	            {LIKE_PATTERN_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
70	
71	    Other Parameters:
72	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \

75	        result_format (str or None): \
76	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
77	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
78	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
79	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
80	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
81	        meta (dict or None): \
82	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \

90	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
91	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
92	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).

87	        result_format (str or None): \
88	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
89	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
90	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
91	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
92	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
93	        meta (dict or None): \
94	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
95	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
96	
97	    Returns:
98	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
99	
100	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
63	class ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegex(ColumnMapExpectation):
64	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
65	
66	    The regex must not match \
67	    any portion of the provided string. For example, "[at]+" would identify the following strings as expected: \
68	    "fish", "dog", and the following as unexpected: "cat", "hat".
69	
70	    ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegex is a \
71	    Column Map Expectation.
72	
73	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
74	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
75	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
76	
77	    Args:
78	        column (str): \
79	            {COLUMN_DESCRIPTION}
80	        regex (str): \
81	            {REGEX_DESCRIPTION}
82	
83	    Other Parameters:
84	                mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
85	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
86	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly).
87	        result_format (str or None): \
88	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
89	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
90	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
91	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
92	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
93	        meta (dict or None): \
94	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
95	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
96	
97	    Returns:
98	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
99	
100	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
101	
102	    See Also:
103	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegex](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_regex)
104	        [ExpectColumnValuesToMatchRegexList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_match_regex_list)
105	        [ExpectColumnValuesToNotMatchRegexList](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_column_values_to_not_match_regex_list)

81	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \

85	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).

61	    Column Map Expectation.
62	
63	    Column Map Expectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
64	    They are evaluated for a single column and ask a yes/no question for every row in that column.
65	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer. If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
51	class ExpectCompoundColumnsToBeUnique(MulticolumnMapExpectation):
52	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
53	
54	    ExpectCompoundColumnsToBeUnique is a \
55	    Multicolumn Map Expectation.
56	
57	    Multicolumn Map Expectations are evaluated for a set of columns and ask a yes/no question about the row-wise relationship between those columns.
58	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer.
59	    If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
60	
61	    Args:
62	        column_list (tuple or list): {COLUMN_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    Other Parameters:
65	        ignore_row_if (str): \
66	            "all_values_are_missing", "any_value_is_missing", "never" \
67	            If specified, sets the condition on which a given row is to be ignored. Default "never".
68	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
69	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
70	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
71	        result_format (str or None): \
72	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
73	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
74	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
75	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
76	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
77	        meta (dict or None): \
78	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
79	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
80	
81	    Returns:
82	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
83

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
51	class ExpectCompoundColumnsToBeUnique(MulticolumnMapExpectation):
52	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
53	
54	    ExpectCompoundColumnsToBeUnique is a \
55	    Multicolumn Map Expectation.
56	
57	    Multicolumn Map Expectations are evaluated for a set of columns and ask a yes/no question about the row-wise relationship between those columns.
58	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer.
59	    If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
60	
61	    Args:
62	        column_list (tuple or list): {COLUMN_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    Other Parameters:
65	        ignore_row_if (str): \
66	            "all_values_are_missing", "any_value_is_missing", "never" \
67	            If specified, sets the condition on which a given row is to be ignored. Default "never".
68	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
69	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
70	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
71	        result_format (str or None): \
72	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
73	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
74	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
75	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
76	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
77	        meta (dict or None): \
78	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
79	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
80	
81	    Returns:
82	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
83	
84	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
85	
86	    Supported Data Sources:
87	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
88	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

67	            If specified, sets the condition on which a given row is to be ignored. Default "never".
68	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
69	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
70	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
71	        result_format (str or None): \
72	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
73	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
74	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
75	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
76	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).

78	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
79	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).

51	class ExpectCompoundColumnsToBeUnique(MulticolumnMapExpectation):
52	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
53	
54	    ExpectCompoundColumnsToBeUnique is a \
55	    Multicolumn Map Expectation.
56	
57	    Multicolumn Map Expectations are evaluated for a set of columns and ask a yes/no question about the row-wise relationship between those columns.
58	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer.
59	    If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
60	
61	    Args:
62	        column_list (tuple or list): {COLUMN_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    Other Parameters:
65	        ignore_row_if (str): \
66	            "all_values_are_missing", "any_value_is_missing", "never" \
67	            If specified, sets the condition on which a given row is to be ignored. Default "never".
68	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
69	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
70	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
71	        result_format (str or None): \
72	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
73	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
74	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
75	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
76	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
77	        meta (dict or None): \
78	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
79	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
80	
81	    Returns:
82	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)

55	class ExpectSelectColumnValuesToBeUniqueWithinRecord(MulticolumnMapExpectation):
56	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
57	
58	    ExpectSelectColumnValuesToBeUniqueWithinRecord is a \
59	    Multicolumn Map Expectation.
60	
61	    Multicolumn Map Expectations are evaluated for a set of columns and ask a yes/no question about the row-wise relationship between those columns.
62	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer.
63	    If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
64	
65	    Args:
66	        column_list (tuple or list): {COLUMN_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
67	
68	    Other Parameters:
69	        ignore_row_if (str): \
70	            "all_values_are_missing", "any_value_is_missing", "never" \
71	            {IGNORE_ROW_IF_DESCRIPTION} Default "never".
72	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
73	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
74	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
75	        result_format (str or None): \
76	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
77	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
78	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
79	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
80	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
81	        meta (dict or None): \
82	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
83	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
84	
85	    Returns:
86	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
87	
88	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
89	
90	    Supported Data Sources:
91	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
92	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
55	class ExpectSelectColumnValuesToBeUniqueWithinRecord(MulticolumnMapExpectation):
56	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
57	
58	    ExpectSelectColumnValuesToBeUniqueWithinRecord is a \
59	    Multicolumn Map Expectation.
60	
61	    Multicolumn Map Expectations are evaluated for a set of columns and ask a yes/no question about the row-wise relationship between those columns.
62	    Based on the result, they then calculate the percentage of rows that gave a positive answer.
63	    If the percentage is high enough, the Expectation considers that data valid.
64	
65	    Args:
66	        column_list (tuple or list): {COLUMN_LIST_DESCRIPTION}
67	
68	    Other Parameters:
69	        ignore_row_if (str): \
70	            "all_values_are_missing", "any_value_is_missing", "never" \
71	            {IGNORE_ROW_IF_DESCRIPTION} Default "never".
72	        mostly (None or a float between 0 and 1): \
73	            {MOSTLY_DESCRIPTION} \
74	            For more detail, see [mostly](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#mostly). Default 1.
75	        result_format (str or None): \
76	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
77	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
78	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
79	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
80	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
81	        meta (dict or None): \
82	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
83	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
84	
85	    Returns:
86	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
87	
88	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
89	
90	    Supported Data Sources:
91	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
92	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
51	class ExpectTableColumnCountToBeBetween(BatchExpectation):
52	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
53	
54	    ExpectTableColumnCountToBeBetween is a \
55	    Batch Expectation.
56	
57	    BatchExpectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
58	    They are evaluated for an entire Batch, and answer a semantic question about the Batch itself.
59	
60	    Args:
61	        min_value (int or None): {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
62	        max_value (int or None): {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    Other Parameters:
65	        result_format (str or None): \
66	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
67	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
68	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
69	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
70	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
71	        meta (dict or None): \
72	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
73	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
74	
75	    Returns:
76	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
77	
78	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
79	
80	    Notes:
81	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive.
82	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and the number of acceptable columns \
83	          has no minimum.
84	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and the number of acceptable columns \
85	          has no maximum.
86	
87	    See Also:
88	        [ExpectTableColumnCountToEqual](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_table_column_count_to_equal)
89	
90	    Supported Data Sources:
91	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
92	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

51	class ExpectTableColumnCountToBeBetween(BatchExpectation):
52	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
53	
54	    ExpectTableColumnCountToBeBetween is a \
55	    Batch Expectation.
56	
57	    BatchExpectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
58	    They are evaluated for an entire Batch, and answer a semantic question about the Batch itself.
59	
60	    Args:
61	        min_value (int or None): {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
62	        max_value (int or None): {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
63	
64	    Other Parameters:
65	        result_format (str or None): \
66	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
67	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
68	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
69	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
70	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
71	        meta (dict or None): \
72	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
73	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
74	
75	    Returns:
76	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
77	
78	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
79	
80	    Notes:
81	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive.
82	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and the number of acceptable columns \
83	          has no minimum.
84	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and the number of acceptable columns \
85	          has no maximum.
86	
87	    See Also:
88	        [ExpectTableColumnCountToEqual](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_table_column_count_to_equal)

   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
64	class ExpectTableRowCountToBeBetween(BatchExpectation):
65	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
66	
67	    ExpectTableRowCountToBeBetween is a \
68	    Batch Expectation.
69	
70	    BatchExpectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
71	    They are evaluated for an entire Batch, and answer a semantic question about the Batch itself.
72	
73	    Args:
74	        min_value (int or None): \
75	            {MIN_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
76	        max_value (int or None): \
77	            {MAX_VALUE_DESCRIPTION}
78	        strict_min (boolean): \
79	            {STRICT_MIN_DESCRIPTION}
80	        strict_max (boolean): \
81	            {STRICT_MAX_DESCRIPTION}
82	
83	    Other Parameters:
84	        result_format (str or None): \
85	            Which output mode to use: BOOLEAN_ONLY, BASIC, COMPLETE, or SUMMARY. \
86	            For more detail, see [result_format](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/result_format).
87	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
88	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
89	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).
90	        meta (dict or None): \
91	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
92	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
93	
94	    Returns:
95	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
96	
97	        Exact fields vary depending on the values passed to result_format, catch_exceptions, and meta.
98	
99	    Notes:
100	        * min_value and max_value are both inclusive unless strict_min or strict_max are set to True.
101	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
102	          no minimum.
103	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
104	          no maximum.
105	
106	    See Also:
107	        [ExpectTableRowCountToEqual](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_table_row_count_to_equal)
108	
109	    Supported Data Sources:
110	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

87	        catch_exceptions (boolean or None): \
88	            If True, then catch exceptions and include them as part of the result object. \
89	            For more detail, see [catch_exceptions](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#catch_exceptions).

96

101	        * If min_value is None, then max_value is treated as an upper bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
102	          no minimum.
103	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
104	          no maximum.

103	        * If max_value is None, then min_value is treated as a lower bound, and the number of acceptable rows has \
104	          no maximum.
105	
106	    See Also:
107	        [ExpectTableRowCountToEqual](https://greatexpectations.io/expectations/expect_table_row_count_to_equal)
108	
109	    Supported Data Sources:
110	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[0]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
111	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[1]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
112	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[2]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)
113	        [{SUPPORTED_DATA_SOURCES[3]}](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/application_integration_support/)

77	        meta (dict or None): \
78	            A JSON-serializable dictionary (nesting allowed) that will be included in the output without \
79	            modification. For more detail, see [meta](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/reference/expectations/standard_arguments/#meta).
80	
81	    Returns:
82	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)

54	class UnexpectedRowsExpectation(BatchExpectation):
55	    __doc__ = f"""{EXPECTATION_SHORT_DESCRIPTION}
56	
57	    UnexpectedRowsExpectations facilitate the execution of SQL or Spark-SQL queries \
58	    as the core logic for an Expectation. UnexpectedRowsExpectations must implement \
59	    a `_validate(...)` method containing logic for determining whether data returned \
60	    by the executed query is successfully validated. One is written by default, but \
61	    can be overridden.
62	
63	    A successful validation is one where the unexpected_rows_query returns no rows.
64	
65	    UnexpectedRowsExpectation is a \
66	    [Batch Expectation](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/guides/expectations/creating_custom_expectations/how_to_create_custom_batch_expectations).
67	
68	    BatchExpectations are one of the most common types of Expectation.
69	    They are evaluated for an entire Batch, and answer a semantic question about the Batch itself.
70	
71	    Args:
72	        unexpected_rows_query (str): {UNEXPECTED_ROWS_QUERY_DESCRIPTION}
73	
74	    Returns:
75	        An [ExpectationSuiteValidationResult](https://docs.greatexpectations.io/docs/terms/validation_result)
