>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/great_expectations-1.3.14/great_expectations-1.3.14/versioneer.py:428
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
427	    "git"
428	] = r'''
429	# This file helps to compute a version number in source trees obtained from
430	# git-archive tarball (such as those provided by githubs download-from-tag
431	# feature). Distribution tarballs (built by setup.py sdist) and build
432	# directories (produced by setup.py build) will contain a much shorter file
433	# that just contains the computed version number.
434	
435	# This file is released into the public domain. Generated by
436	# versioneer-0.18 (https://github.com/warner/python-versioneer)
437	
438	"""Git implementation of _version.py."""
439	
440	import errno
441	import os
442	import re
443	import subprocess
444	import sys
445	
446	
447	def get_keywords():
448	    """Get the keywords needed to look up the version information."""
449	    # these strings will be replaced by git during git-archive.
450	    # setup.py/versioneer.py will grep for the variable names, so they must
451	    # each be defined on a line of their own. _version.py will just call
452	    # get_keywords().
453	    git_refnames = "%(DOLLAR)sFormat:%%d%(DOLLAR)s"
454	    git_full = "%(DOLLAR)sFormat:%%H%(DOLLAR)s"
455	    git_date = "%(DOLLAR)sFormat:%%ci%(DOLLAR)s"
456	    keywords = {"refnames": git_refnames, "full": git_full, "date": git_date}
457	    return keywords
458	
459	
460	class VersioneerConfig:
461	    """Container for Versioneer configuration parameters."""
462	
463	
464	def get_config():
465	    """Create, populate and return the VersioneerConfig() object."""
466	    # these strings are filled in when 'setup.py versioneer' creates
467	    # _version.py
468	    cfg = VersioneerConfig()
469	    cfg.VCS = "git"
470	    cfg.style = "%(STYLE)s"
471	    cfg.tag_prefix = "%(TAG_PREFIX)s"
472	    cfg.parentdir_prefix = "%(PARENTDIR_PREFIX)s"
473	    cfg.versionfile_source = "%(VERSIONFILE_SOURCE)s"
474	    cfg.verbose = False
475	    return cfg
476	
477	
478	class NotThisMethod(Exception):
479	    """Exception raised if a method is not valid for the current scenario."""
480	
481	
482	LONG_VERSION_PY = {}
483	HANDLERS = {}
484	
485	
486	def register_vcs_handler(vcs, method):  # decorator
487	    """Decorator to mark a method as the handler for a particular VCS."""
488	    def decorate(f):
489	        """Store f in HANDLERS[vcs][method]."""
490	        if vcs not in HANDLERS:
491	            HANDLERS[vcs] = {}
492	        HANDLERS[vcs][method] = f
493	        return f
494	    return decorate
495	
496	
497	def run_command(commands, args, cwd=None, verbose=False, hide_stderr=False,
498	                env=None):
499	    """Call the given command(s)."""
500	    assert isinstance(commands, list)
501	    p = None
502	    for c in commands:
503	        try:
504	            dispcmd = str([c] + args)
505	            # remember shell=False, so use git.cmd on windows, not just git
506	            p = subprocess.Popen([c] + args, cwd=cwd, env=env,
507	                                 stdout=subprocess.PIPE,
508	                                 stderr=(subprocess.PIPE if hide_stderr
509	                                         else None))
510	            break
511	        except EnvironmentError:
512	            e = sys.exc_info()[1]
513	            if e.errno == errno.ENOENT:
514	                continue
515	            if verbose:
516	                print("unable to run %%s" %% dispcmd)
517	                print(e)
518	            return None, None
519	    else:
520	        if verbose:
521	            print("unable to find command, tried %%s" %% (commands,))
522	        return None, None
523	    stdout = p.communicate()[0].strip()
524	    if sys.version_info[0] >= 3:
525	        stdout = stdout.decode()
526	    if p.returncode != 0:
527	        if verbose:
528	            print("unable to run %%s (error)" %% dispcmd)
529	            print("stdout was %%s" %% stdout)
530	        return None, p.returncode
531	    return stdout, p.returncode
532	
533	
534	def versions_from_parentdir(parentdir_prefix, root, verbose):
535	    """Try to determine the version from the parent directory name.
536	
537	    Source tarballs conventionally unpack into a directory that includes both
538	    the project name and a version string. We will also support searching up
539	    two directory levels for an appropriately named parent directory
540	    """
541	    rootdirs = []
542	
543	    for i in range(3):
544	        dirname = os.path.basename(root)
545	        if dirname.startswith(parentdir_prefix):
546	            return {"version": dirname[len(parentdir_prefix):],
547	                    "full-revisionid": None,
548	                    "dirty": False, "error": None, "date": None}
549	        else:
550	            rootdirs.append(root)
551	            root = os.path.dirname(root)  # up a level
552	
553	    if verbose:
554	        print("Tried directories %%s but none started with prefix %%s" %%
555	              (str(rootdirs), parentdir_prefix))
556	    raise NotThisMethod("rootdir doesn't start with parentdir_prefix")
557	
558	
559	@register_vcs_handler("git", "get_keywords")
560	def git_get_keywords(versionfile_abs):
561	    """Extract version information from the given file."""
562	    # the code embedded in _version.py can just fetch the value of these
563	    # keywords. When used from setup.py, we don't want to import _version.py,
564	    # so we do it with a regexp instead. This function is not used from
565	    # _version.py.
566	    keywords = {}
567	    try:
568	        f = open(versionfile_abs, "r")
569	        for line in f.readlines():
570	            if line.strip().startswith("git_refnames ="):
571	                mo = re.search(r'=\s*"(.*)"', line)
572	                if mo:
573	                    keywords["refnames"] = mo.group(1)
574	            if line.strip().startswith("git_full ="):
575	                mo = re.search(r'=\s*"(.*)"', line)
576	                if mo:
577	                    keywords["full"] = mo.group(1)
578	            if line.strip().startswith("git_date ="):
579	                mo = re.search(r'=\s*"(.*)"', line)
580	                if mo:
581	                    keywords["date"] = mo.group(1)
582	        f.close()
583	    except EnvironmentError:
584	        pass
585	    return keywords
586	
587	
588	@register_vcs_handler("git", "keywords")
589	def git_versions_from_keywords(keywords, tag_prefix, verbose):
590	    """Get version information from git keywords."""
591	    if not keywords:
592	        raise NotThisMethod("no keywords at all, weird")
593	    date = keywords.get("date")
594	    if date is not None:
595	        # git-2.2.0 added "%%cI", which expands to an ISO-8601 -compliant
596	        # datestamp. However we prefer "%%ci" (which expands to an "ISO-8601
597	        # -like" string, which we must then edit to make compliant), because
598	        # it's been around since git-1.5.3, and it's too difficult to
599	        # discover which version we're using, or to work around using an
600	        # older one.
601	        date = date.strip().replace(" ", "T", 1).replace(" ", "", 1)
602	    refnames = keywords["refnames"].strip()
603	    if refnames.startswith("$Format"):
604	        if verbose:
605	            print("keywords are unexpanded, not using")
606	        raise NotThisMethod("unexpanded keywords, not a git-archive tarball")
607	    refs = set([r.strip() for r in refnames.strip("()").split(",")])
608	    # starting in git-1.8.3, tags are listed as "tag: foo-1.0" instead of
609	    # just "foo-1.0". If we see a "tag: " prefix, prefer those.
610	    TAG = "tag: "
611	    tags = set([r[len(TAG):] for r in refs if r.startswith(TAG)])
612	    if not tags:
613	        # Either we're using git < 1.8.3, or there really are no tags. We use
614	        # a heuristic: assume all version tags have a digit. The old git %%d
615	        # expansion behaves like git log --decorate=short and strips out the
616	        # refs/heads/ and refs/tags/ prefixes that would let us distinguish
617	        # between branches and tags. By ignoring refnames without digits, we
618	        # filter out many common branch names like "release" and
619	        # "stabilization", as well as "HEAD" and "master".
620	        tags = set([r for r in refs if re.search(r'\d', r)])
621	        if verbose:
622	            print("discarding '%%s', no digits" %% ",".join(refs - tags))
623	    if verbose:
624	        print("likely tags: %%s" %% ",".join(sorted(tags)))
625	    for ref in sorted(tags):
626	        # sorting will prefer e.g. "2.0" over "2.0rc1"
627	        if ref.startswith(tag_prefix):
628	            r = ref[len(tag_prefix):]
629	            if verbose:
630	                print("picking %%s" %% r)
631	            return {"version": r,
632	                    "full-revisionid": keywords["full"].strip(),
633	                    "dirty": False, "error": None,
634	                    "date": date}
635	    # no suitable tags, so version is "0+unknown", but full hex is still there
636	    if verbose:
637	        print("no suitable tags, using unknown + full revision id")
638	    return {"version": "0+unknown",
639	            "full-revisionid": keywords["full"].strip(),
640	            "dirty": False, "error": "no suitable tags", "date": None}
641	
642	
643	@register_vcs_handler("git", "pieces_from_vcs")
644	def git_pieces_from_vcs(tag_prefix, root, verbose, run_command=run_command):
645	    """Get version from 'git describe' in the root of the source tree.
646	
647	    This only gets called if the git-archive 'subst' keywords were *not*
648	    expanded, and _version.py hasn't already been rewritten with a short
649	    version string, meaning we're inside a checked out source tree.
650	    """
651	    GITS = ["git"]
652	    if sys.platform == "win32":
653	        GITS = ["git.cmd", "git.exe"]
654	
655	    out, rc = run_command(GITS, ["rev-parse", "--git-dir"], cwd=root,
656	                          hide_stderr=True)
657	    if rc != 0:
658	        if verbose:
659	            print("Directory %%s not under git control" %% root)
660	        raise NotThisMethod("'git rev-parse --git-dir' returned error")
661	
662	    # if there is a tag matching tag_prefix, this yields TAG-NUM-gHEX[-dirty]
663	    # if there isn't one, this yields HEX[-dirty] (no NUM)
664	    describe_out, rc = run_command(GITS, ["describe", "--tags", "--dirty",
665	                                          "--always", "--long",
666	                                          "--match", "%%s*" %% tag_prefix],
667	                                   cwd=root)
668	    # --long was added in git-1.5.5
669	    if describe_out is None:
670	        raise NotThisMethod("'git describe' failed")
671	    describe_out = describe_out.strip()
672	    full_out, rc = run_command(GITS, ["rev-parse", "HEAD"], cwd=root)
673	    if full_out is None:
674	        raise NotThisMethod("'git rev-parse' failed")
675	    full_out = full_out.strip()
676	
677	    pieces = {}
678	    pieces["long"] = full_out
679	    pieces["short"] = full_out[:7]  # maybe improved later
680	    pieces["error"] = None
681	
682	    # parse describe_out. It will be like TAG-NUM-gHEX[-dirty] or HEX[-dirty]
683	    # TAG might have hyphens.
684	    git_describe = describe_out
685	
686	    # look for -dirty suffix
687	    dirty = git_describe.endswith("-dirty")
688	    pieces["dirty"] = dirty
689	    if dirty:
690	        git_describe = git_describe[:git_describe.rindex("-dirty")]
691	
692	    # now we have TAG-NUM-gHEX or HEX
693	
694	    if "-" in git_describe:
695	        # TAG-NUM-gHEX
696	        mo = re.search(r'^(.+)-(\d+)-g([0-9a-f]+)$', git_describe)
697	        if not mo:
698	            # unparsable. Maybe git-describe is misbehaving?
699	            pieces["error"] = ("unable to parse git-describe output: '%%s'"
700	                               %% describe_out)
701	            return pieces
702	
703	        # tag
704	        full_tag = mo.group(1)
705	        if not full_tag.startswith(tag_prefix):
706	            if verbose:
707	                fmt = "tag '%%s' doesn't start with prefix '%%s'"
708	                print(fmt %% (full_tag, tag_prefix))
709	            pieces["error"] = ("tag '%%s' doesn't start with prefix '%%s'"
710	                               %% (full_tag, tag_prefix))
711	            return pieces
712	        pieces["closest-tag"] = full_tag[len(tag_prefix):]
713	
714	        # distance: number of commits since tag
715	        pieces["distance"] = int(mo.group(2))
716	
717	        # commit: short hex revision ID
718	        pieces["short"] = mo.group(3)
719	
720	    else:
721	        # HEX: no tags
722	        pieces["closest-tag"] = None
723	        count_out, rc = run_command(GITS, ["rev-list", "HEAD", "--count"],
724	                                    cwd=root)
725	        pieces["distance"] = int(count_out)  # total number of commits
726	
727	    # commit date: see ISO-8601 comment in git_versions_from_keywords()
728	    date = run_command(GITS, ["show", "-s", "--format=%%ci", "HEAD"],
729	                       cwd=root)[0].strip()
730	    pieces["date"] = date.strip().replace(" ", "T", 1).replace(" ", "", 1)
731	
732	    return pieces
733	
734	
735	def plus_or_dot(pieces):
736	    """Return a + if we don't already have one, else return a ."""
737	    if "+" in pieces.get("closest-tag", ""):
738	        return "."
739	    return "+"
740	
741	
742	def render_pep440(pieces):
743	    """Build up version string, with post-release "local version identifier".
744	
745	    Our goal: TAG[+DISTANCE.gHEX[.dirty]] . Note that if you
746	    get a tagged build and then dirty it, you'll get TAG+0.gHEX.dirty
747	
748	    Exceptions:
749	    1: no tags. git_describe was just HEX. 0+untagged.DISTANCE.gHEX[.dirty]
750	    """
751	    if pieces["closest-tag"]:
752	        rendered = pieces["closest-tag"]
753	        if pieces["distance"] or pieces["dirty"]:
754	            rendered += plus_or_dot(pieces)
755	            rendered += "%%d.g%%s" %% (pieces["distance"], pieces["short"])
756	            if pieces["dirty"]:
757	                rendered += ".dirty"
758	    else:
759	        # exception #1
760	        rendered = "0+untagged.%%d.g%%s" %% (pieces["distance"],
761	                                          pieces["short"])
762	        if pieces["dirty"]:
763	            rendered += ".dirty"
764	    return rendered
765	
766	
767	def render_pep440_pre(pieces):
768	    """TAG[.post.devDISTANCE] -- No -dirty.
769	
770	    Exceptions:
771	    1: no tags. 0.post.devDISTANCE
772	    """
773	    if pieces["closest-tag"]:
774	        rendered = pieces["closest-tag"]
775	        if pieces["distance"]:
776	            rendered += ".post.dev%%d" %% pieces["distance"]
777	    else:
778	        # exception #1
779	        rendered = "0.post.dev%%d" %% pieces["distance"]
780	    return rendered
781	
782	
783	def render_pep440_post(pieces):
784	    """TAG[.postDISTANCE[.dev0]+gHEX] .
785	
786	    The ".dev0" means dirty. Note that .dev0 sorts backwards
787	    (a dirty tree will appear "older" than the corresponding clean one),
788	    but you shouldn't be releasing software with -dirty anyways.
789	
790	    Exceptions:
791	    1: no tags. 0.postDISTANCE[.dev0]
792	    """
793	    if pieces["closest-tag"]:
794	        rendered = pieces["closest-tag"]
795	        if pieces["distance"] or pieces["dirty"]:
796	            rendered += ".post%%d" %% pieces["distance"]
797	            if pieces["dirty"]:
798	                rendered += ".dev0"
799	            rendered += plus_or_dot(pieces)
800	            rendered += "g%%s" %% pieces["short"]
801	    else:
802	        # exception #1
803	        rendered = "0.post%%d" %% pieces["distance"]
804	        if pieces["dirty"]:
805	            rendered += ".dev0"
806	        rendered += "+g%%s" %% pieces["short"]
807	    return rendered
808	
809	
810	def render_pep440_old(pieces):
811	    """TAG[.postDISTANCE[.dev0]] .
812	
813	    The ".dev0" means dirty.
814	
815	    Eexceptions:
816	    1: no tags. 0.postDISTANCE[.dev0]
817	    """
818	    if pieces["closest-tag"]:
819	        rendered = pieces["closest-tag"]
820	        if pieces["distance"] or pieces["dirty"]:
821	            rendered += ".post%%d" %% pieces["distance"]
822	            if pieces["dirty"]:
823	                rendered += ".dev0"
824	    else:
825	        # exception #1
826	        rendered = "0.post%%d" %% pieces["distance"]
827	        if pieces["dirty"]:
828	            rendered += ".dev0"
829	    return rendered
830	
831	
832	def render_git_describe(pieces):
833	    """TAG[-DISTANCE-gHEX][-dirty].
834	
835	    Like 'git describe --tags --dirty --always'.
836	
837	    Exceptions:
838	    1: no tags. HEX[-dirty]  (note: no 'g' prefix)
839	    """
840	    if pieces["closest-tag"]:
841	        rendered = pieces["closest-tag"]
842	        if pieces["distance"]:
843	            rendered += "-%%d-g%%s" %% (pieces["distance"], pieces["short"])
844	    else:
845	        # exception #1
846	        rendered = pieces["short"]
847	    if pieces["dirty"]:
848	        rendered += "-dirty"
849	    return rendered
850	
851	
852	def render_git_describe_long(pieces):
853	    """TAG-DISTANCE-gHEX[-dirty].
854	
855	    Like 'git describe --tags --dirty --always -long'.
856	    The distance/hash is unconditional.
857	
858	    Exceptions:
859	    1: no tags. HEX[-dirty]  (note: no 'g' prefix)
860	    """
861	    if pieces["closest-tag"]:
862	        rendered = pieces["closest-tag"]
863	        rendered += "-%%d-g%%s" %% (pieces["distance"], pieces["short"])
864	    else:
865	        # exception #1
866	        rendered = pieces["short"]
867	    if pieces["dirty"]:
868	        rendered += "-dirty"
869	    return rendered
870	
871	
872	def render(pieces, style):
873	    """Render the given version pieces into the requested style."""
874	    if pieces["error"]:
875	        return {"version": "unknown",
876	                "full-revisionid": pieces.get("long"),
877	                "dirty": None,
878	                "error": pieces["error"],
879	                "date": None}
880	
881	    if not style or style == "default":
882	        style = "pep440"  # the default
883	
884	    if style == "pep440":
885	        rendered = render_pep440(pieces)
886	    elif style == "pep440-pre":
887	        rendered = render_pep440_pre(pieces)
888	    elif style == "pep440-post":
889	        rendered = render_pep440_post(pieces)
890	    elif style == "pep440-old":
891	        rendered = render_pep440_old(pieces)
892	    elif style == "git-describe":
893	        rendered = render_git_describe(pieces)
894	    elif style == "git-describe-long":
895	        rendered = render_git_describe_long(pieces)
896	    else:
897	        raise ValueError("unknown style '%%s'" %% style)
898	
899	    return {"version": rendered, "full-revisionid": pieces["long"],
900	            "dirty": pieces["dirty"], "error": None,
901	            "date": pieces.get("date")}
902	
903	
904	def get_versions():
905	    """Get version information or return default if unable to do so."""
906	    # I am in _version.py, which lives at ROOT/VERSIONFILE_SOURCE. If we have
907	    # __file__, we can work backwards from there to the root. Some
908	    # py2exe/bbfreeze/non-CPython implementations don't do __file__, in which
909	    # case we can only use expanded keywords.
910	
911	    cfg = get_config()
912	    verbose = cfg.verbose
913	
914	    try:
915	        return git_versions_from_keywords(get_keywords(), cfg.tag_prefix,
916	                                          verbose)
917	    except NotThisMethod:
918	        pass
919	
920	    try:
921	        root = os.path.realpath(__file__)
922	        # versionfile_source is the relative path from the top of the source
923	        # tree (where the .git directory might live) to this file. Invert
924	        # this to find the root from __file__.
925	        for i in cfg.versionfile_source.split('/'):
926	            root = os.path.dirname(root)
927	    except NameError:
928	        return {"version": "0+unknown", "full-revisionid": None,
929	                "dirty": None,
930	                "error": "unable to find root of source tree",
931	                "date": None}
932	
933	    try:
934	        pieces = git_pieces_from_vcs(cfg.tag_prefix, root, verbose)
935	        return render(pieces, cfg.style)
936	    except NotThisMethod:
937	        pass
938	
939	    try:
940	        if cfg.parentdir_prefix:
941	            return versions_from_parentdir(cfg.parentdir_prefix, root, verbose)
942	    except NotThisMethod:
943	        pass
944	
945	    return {"version": "0+unknown", "full-revisionid": None,
946	            "dirty": None,
947	            "error": "unable to compute version", "date": None}
948	'''
949	
950
